---
description: Require confirmation dialogs before any destructive delete action
alwaysApply: true
---

# Delete Confirmations

Any UI that **deletes** data (records, nested structure, submissions, etc.) must ask for confirmation before submitting the delete action. Do not delete on a single click.

## Required pattern

1. Use Radix **Alert Dialog** (`@radix-ui/react-alert-dialog`) — same pattern as `DeleteSubmissionButton`
2. Trigger opens the dialog; only the dialog’s confirm control submits the Server Action / form
3. Include a clear title, short consequence description, **Cancel**, and a destructive confirm button
4. Prefer an existing shared wrapper under `src/components/` when one exists; otherwise follow the inline Alert Dialog pattern already in the app

```js
// ✅ GOOD — confirm, then submit
<AlertDialog.Root>
  <AlertDialog.Trigger asChild>
    <button type="button">Delete</button>
  </AlertDialog.Trigger>
  <AlertDialog.Portal>
    {/* overlay + title + description */}
    <form action={deleteAction}>
      <AlertDialog.Cancel asChild>
        <Button type="button">Cancel</Button>
      </AlertDialog.Cancel>
      <Button type="submit">Delete</Button>
    </form>
  </AlertDialog.Portal>
</AlertDialog.Root>
```

```js
// ❌ BAD — immediate delete
<button type="submit" formAction={deleteAction}>Delete</button>
<form action={deleteAction}>
  <button type="submit">Delete</button>
</form>
```

## Scope

Applies to domains, attributes, statements, submissions, users, and any future delete controls — including icon-only or “×” delete buttons.

## Avoid

- `window.confirm` / `confirm()` — use Radix Alert Dialog
- Custom modal implementations when Alert Dialog already fits
- Skipping confirmation because the action “feels small” or is admin-only
